post_text:
Did you know that Genesee Valley Central School has an Urgent Care?

The GVCS Urgent Care is open Monday-Friday during school hours 7:40 a.m. - 3:00 p.m.

In addition to treating non-emergent medical needs such as ear infections, pink eye, allergies, skin abnormalities, and more, the GVCS Urgent Care can uniquely test students and employees for COVID-19, Influenza, Strep Throat, and Urinalysis.

To take advantage of the GVCS Urgent Care, students must be enrolled in the program. Once enrolled, when a student becomes ill while they're in school, a provider from our tele-medicine partner (Mobile Primary Care) can quickly assess their symptoms and get them tested before they leave campus.

If you would like to enroll your child in the Urgent Care/Tele-medical program, please have your insurance information ready, use access code: 287111, and visit this website: https://form.jotform.com/92653014669159.

Please contact Anne Campbell, Wellness Director, with questions at acampbell@genvalley.org or 585-268-7900, ext. 1216.

Dear GVCS Parents,

We realize the challenges that COVID-19 presents to working parents in need of childcare when school reopens. In an effort to help GV families, we have created a list of high school students who are interested in babysitting for the children of working parents. (These high school students would only be able to babysit on days when they are not in the school building.) Students available for babysitting will have completed a babysitting online training, a First Aid/CPR online training and be a student in good standing (grades and attendance to be approved by the building principal).

If you are a parent in need of childcare once school reopens, please contact Paula Mighells, Dean of Students/Curriculum Coordinator, at 585-268-7942 weekdays between 8:00 a.m.-3:00 p.m. or email at pmighells@genvalley.org.

Laura Platt is a member of the Genesee Valley class of 2008. She lives in Portland, OR with her partner Geoff and their three chickens! She is a member of the Research Staff in the Global Environmental Change Lab at Portland State University. In this role she leads field crews to collect dendroecological (aka, tree ring) data in the mid-elevation forests of northeastern Oregon.

After graduating from GV, Laura earned her B.S. in Biology from SUNY Cortland and her M.S. in Geography (with a specialization in Forest Ecology and Dendroecology) from Portland State.

Laura has fond memories of playing volleyball at GV and is appreciative of the opportunity she had to take college course while in high school. â€œTaking college-level Calculus, French, Freshman Comp, and Biology while still in high school really gave me a leg up in my time as an undergraduate student.â€ An influential teacher at GV for Laura was Ms. Kristin Buchholz, who taught her â€œart, yoga and acceptance.â€

GVCS ALUMNI SPOTLIGHT --> Josh Crego graduated from Genesee Valley in 2011 and currently lives in Angelica, NY. After GV he attended SUNY Alfred for Business Administration and Interdisciplinary Studies.

Josh is a Regional Product Specialist at Siemens where he does inside sales for aftermarket parts for the Wellsville Steam Turbine product line, specifically working in the Pacific Region in the US.

A favorite memory from his time at GVCS was winning Basketball Sectionals in 2009. Joshâ€™s favorite teacher was Mr. Horton.

â€œGV taught me the value of community and relationships,â€ said Josh. â€œI still live in the GV district and itâ€™s great that people have watched us grow and never stopped wanting us to succeed, even long after we graduated from school.â€

Meals will be delivered to students on Wednesday and Friday of this week . Community meal distributions will continue on Wednesday, June 24 and Friday, June 26 in Angelica (12:00-12:30) and Belmont (12:45-1:15).

Starting Monday, June 29, our Summer Feed Program begins and runs thru Friday August 14. We will be at two remote locations Monday-Friday.

The Angelica pick-up is scheduled at the village Offices from 10:30-11:00 a.m.

The Belmont pick-up is scheduled at the GVCS pool vestibule from 11:30-12:00 p.m.

â€œCameron has found his passion in emergency medical services,â€ said Mrs. Scholes. â€œHe is very talented, skilled and driven when helping others in need. He will excel in this next chapter of his life.â€

Boxes of produce through the Farmers to Families Program are available today! Boxes are for any district resident and may be picked up at the bus garage behind the school between the hours of 3:30-5:00. (Just follow the signs!)

Students who are delivered meals will receive their produce box along with their normal meal delivery.

Each box will contain 5 lbs. potatoes, 4 lbs. oranges, 3 lbs. apples, 3 lbs. onions, 3 lbs. green vegetable, 2 lbs. carrots. (Produce may vary each week.)

Approximately 100 boxes will be available. (One box per family. First come-first served.)

Contact Anne Campbell, GV Wellness Director with questions at acampbell@genvalley.org or 585-268-7933.

Congratulations to Isabelle Ordway, a senior at Genesee Valley Central School. After graduation Isabelle will be going into the United States Army.

â€œBelle is a wonderful student and I absolutely loved coaching her in soccer and golf,â€ said Mrs. Schneider. â€œI asked her to be goalie because no one else would step up to the plate during her sophomore year. Without hesitation, she â€˜doveâ€™ right in! (Slight pun there as â€˜divingâ€™ wasnâ€™t her favorite thing to do.) â€œDustin is a hard working guy who will do well in his element,â€ added Mrs. Schneider. â€œHe has a great personality and shows immense respect for meâ€”I will miss giving him sneakers for class next year! Good luck Dustin!!â€

Starting Weds, June 3, boxes of fresh produce ðŸŽðŸŠðŸ¥•ðŸ¥¦ðŸ¥” will be available to GV District residents. These boxes of fruits and vegetables are provided by the USDA Farmers for Families Food Box Program. They are completely free of charge! (Special thanks to James Desiderio Inc. and Your Local Produce Connection.)

No need to register or apply in advance. Just come to the GV bus garage (behind the school) to pickup your box of produce between the hours of 3:30-5:00 p.m. on Weds. You may pick up one box (20 lbs) per family. First come-first served.

Students who are currently being delivered breakfast and lunch will automatically receive one box of food biweekly until the delivery program ends on June 26. After June 26 families may continue to obtain produce at the bus garage every other week.

More details can be found on the GV website: https://www.genvalley.org/Page/3123

Contact Anne Campbell, GV Wellness Director with questions at acampbell@genvalley.org or 585-268-7933.

Nolan Coble, Genesee Valley class of 2016, was named "Most Outstanding Undergraduate Student" in the School of Arts and Sciences at The College at Brockport State University of New York.

A double major in physics and mathematics, Nolan will attend the University of Maryland in the fall to pursue a PhD in applied mathematics.

Read the article here: https://bit.ly/2XHu739

The masks were made using a design called â€œThe Montana Mask" that Mark found on www.makethemasks.com.

â€œThis particular mask looks like something from the Star Wars universe,â€ said Mark. â€œIt allows users to change out a small piece of filtering material to get multiple uses out of a single N95 hospital mask. This extends the usage of a single mask, is more comfortable for the user, and may be sterilized between uses.â€

Thank you, Mark! We're #GVProud!

CheyAnn Shipman is a 2017 Genesee Valley grad. She is a nationally-certified EMT and works in the bone marrow transplant unit at the Brook Army Medical Center at Fort Sam Houston, Texas.

CheyAnn monitors patient vitals, transports patients to MRIs and X-rays, draws blood and inserts IVs, administers medication, and assists patients and nurses with anything they might need.

â€œRight now is an extra hard time for our patients,â€ said CheyAnn. â€œTheir cancer makes it easy to catch the virus and their immune system canâ€™t fight it. Because of this we are taking extra precautions to keep them safe.â€

CheyAnn, thank you for serving your patients with such care and concern. You make us #GVProud!

Jessica (Mascho) Salmonson graduated from Genesee Valley in 2007 and works as an LPN at Universal Primary Care in Olean, NY. She is currently attending SUNY JCC for her RN and graduated last year from CA BOCES with her LPN. â€œIt may have taken me longer than most people to get to where I am now,â€ said Jessica, â€œbut it just goes to show that it is never too late to follow your dreams!â€

â€œThe pandemic has caused daily life to be scary and stressful,â€ continued Jessica. â€œIt puts the things that are most important in your life into perspective. The best thing this pandemic has done is brought out the kindness in each other and throughout our communities. I hope that when this is all over we will all continue to be kind and help those in need. Thank you to everyone working on the frontlines and to everyone working from home and following the guidelines to keep their family safe.â€

Jessica, weâ€™re #GVProud of how youâ€™ve pursued your dream and for how you are selflessly serving those in need day in and day out.

Lindsey Baker is a 2018 Genesee Valley graduate working part-time as an EMT-B for Medical Transport Service. She also volunteers for 5 different Rescue Squads throughout the county: Angelica, Amity, Friendship, Wellsville and Andover. Prior to the COVID-19 pandemic, Lindsey also worked as a receptionist at the WellNow Urgent Care Center in Olean, NY.

â€œCOVID-19 has changed our procedures as EMTs,â€ said Lindsey. â€œWe treat every call as if itâ€™s a possible COVID-19 patient. So, with every patient we are wearing our goggles, mask and gloves!

Lindsey is especially thankful for the opportunity to attend BOCES for their Medical Assisting program: â€œBOCES helped me prepare for my job now,â€ Lindsey said. â€œIn my work as an EMT I make use of a lot of skills that our teacher taught all of us!â€

Lindsey, thanks for giving so much of your time to be on call when others are in need. You make us #GVProud!

Melissa Francisco graduated from Genesee Valley in 2004 and earned her nursing degrees at Alfred State College and Roberts Wesleyan College.

She is currently an assistant Nurse Manager at Golisano Children's Hospital in Rochester, NY, where she cares for pediatric patients (0-18 years old) who are receiving chemotherapy or have a blood disorder requiring hospitalization.

â€œCOVID-19 thankfully doesn't appear to affect children as severely as adults,â€ said Melissa. â€œBecause of this, my unit has been sending nurses to assist the adult units who could use extra hands to care for patients.â€

As a leader on her team, Melissa is thankful for the community and lessons learned at Gen Valley: â€œI believe a lot of my teamwork mentality came from growing up at GV in a small, tight knit community with friends/teachers I knew my entire time there.â€

Thanks, Melissa, for the way you model the values of teamwork and community each day. You make us #GVProud

Myranda Gumtow is a physical therapist at Maple City Physical Therapy in Hornell, NY. She graduated from Genesee Valley in 2010, earned her bachelorâ€™s degree at St. Bonaventure University and her doctorate in physical therapy from Gannon University.

At Maple City PT she primarily treats patients with orthopedic and neurological conditions. â€œDuring the COVID-19 crisis,â€ said Myranda, â€œwe have had to change our way of treating patients from more of a hands-on technique to telehealthâ€”but we are glad we can still continue to help in anyway!â€

Myranda is grateful for Ms. Bullock, her chemistry teacher at GV: â€œshe helped me through a lot of the science courses that I thought I would never understand! When I went to Bonaventure, chemistry was one of my most difficult classes and I was glad I took Ms. Bullockâ€™s course in high school!â€

Daily Sequence of Bugle Calls

Donna Cowburn Slawson shared a link to the group: Where in the World is GV?
April 10 at 12:00 PM Â·

â€œ5:30!! We have to be at school at 5:30.â€ This is usually one of the first questions about the itinerary. You donâ€™t have to be up at 5:30 to join us this year, but enjoy the video of the different daily sequence of bugle calls.

Reveille comes from the French word "rÃ©veiller" or in English to "to wake up." In 1812, U.S. forces designated the iconic melody to call service members to muster up for roll call to start the work day. It appears there is no official composer of the tune, which is used by about six countries like Denmark, Ireland, and Sweden to mark the start of the day. The notes for each country do vary and they all have written different lyrics as well.

Where are our band kids at? Take a recording of you playing reveille and post them for us to enjoy!

Hannah Gordon is a 2018 Genesee Valley grad who is currently attending St. John Fisher College pursuing a BSN. She works as a Patient Care Technician at Rochester General Hospital assisting nurses and helping patients with daily hygiene, skin care, vital signs, taking lab samples, transporting patients and ambulating patients.

â€œI am at risk every day with the multiple COVID-19 patients we have on our floor,â€ said Hannah. â€œWe are allowed one mask per week to be worn at all times, and our PPE is currently having a shortage, as many hospitals are experiencing nationwide.â€

At GV Hannah participated in the BOCES New Visions Health Professions Program. â€œNew Visions allowed me to begin my education in healthcare during my senior year of high school,â€ said Hannah. â€œI was able to be in the hospital doing clinical twice a week and learn about healthcare and why health care workers choose to do what they do, and how even without a pandemic, they rise above any obstacles every single day.â€

Hannah, thank you for your sacrificial service day in and day out. You make us #GVProud.

post_text:
A couple of GV athletes (along with one former GV athlete) received some post-season awards this week.

GV Boys Basketball seniors Cody Schneider and Evan Windus were named Big 30 All-Stars. Schneider, who averaged 23.7 points/game for the Jaguars this season, was named a 1st team all star. Windus, averaging 22.3 points/game, was named to the 2nd team.

2016 GV grad Andrew Edmister, a senior at Alfred University, was named an ECAC Merit Medal and Morley Award winner for men's swimming and diving. The award is given to senior athletes who excel both academically and athletically. Andrew was a 4-year member of the swimming and diving team as well as team captain.

Congrats Cody, Evan and Andrew!

ðŸ”¥DON'T FALL IN THE LAVA!ðŸ”¥

Get moving this week by practicing your math facts! To get started grab some paper ðŸ“’, something to write with ðŸ–, and some tape!

YOUR MISSION:

Cross the room, without touching the floor (lava), using ONLY your knowledge of math facts!

HOW TO PLAY:

1. Choose the type of facts that best fits the player's level: addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, or a mix!

2. Decide where the "start" and "end" will be for the mission.

3. Explain that one math fact will be written on the piece of paper. If the player answers CORRECTLY, the piece of paper will be taped to the floor as a "stepping stone" to get to the end without falling in the lava.

4. If the question is answered INCORRECTLY, the player cannot move forward and will get another question.

5. When the player reaches the end, they have won their mission!

WANT AN ADDED CHALLENGE?

How fast can you get through the lava? Play again and time yourself to see if you can get there faster!

Attention any student (mostly 11th graders and a few 10th graders) that signed up for the SAT and/or ACT. The only dates available for testing now are June 13th for the ACT and June 6th for the SAT. (The April ACT, March SAT, and May SAT are all cancelled.) You should be able to receive a refund or switch to the June dates.

Also, to all 9-12 grade students please be watching your email today and tomorrow for some important information on scheduling for next school year, SAT/ACT registration help, BOCES CTE registration, etc. These deadlines are very important so please respond ASAP!

Please contact Mrs Preston with any questions or concerns at jpreston@genvalley.org. Thank you!

Our "Meet the Teacher" feature continues today with Mr. Lyn VanTassel, science teacher extraordinaire! Mr. VanTassel is finishing his 38th year teaching, including 23 years at Genesee Valley.

â€œI have worked in 4 schools in my career and hands down, GV firms the tightest bonds between the staff, students and community. From our bus drivers, custodians, teachers, support staff and all the way to our Superintendent, everyone has a single goal in helping students.â€

Mr. VanTasselâ€™s students have done quite well on the earth science regents and he is looking forward to this yearâ€™s group finding success. â€œI donâ€™t view teaching as work,â€ he says. â€œI come to school and find ways to make the learning process fun and joyful while pushing students to grow in Earth Science.â€

Mr. VanTassel graced the stage earlier this year as Mr. Pulitzer in GVâ€™s production of Newsies. He has also served as the math/science department chairperson for the past two years. Outside of GV, he enjoys the outdoors and is an avid hunter and fisherman as well as a camping enthusiast.

Many have been asking about how to access technology resources while we move to an online learning format for the foreseeable future. We will be providing iPads to any grade 4-12 students who are in need of a device. iPads will be available on the daily meal bus runs and for pick-up between the hours of noon and 1:00 p.m. at the Village Offices in Angelica and the American Legion in Belmont.

You are welcome to use your own device if you have a Windows/Mac laptop or desktop or an iOS/Android device and are able to access Microsoft Teams.

We are also compiling a list of free Wi-Fi locations in the area.

For more details please visit: https://www.genvalley.org/Page/2078

Weâ€™re taking a trip to the second floor today to introduce you to Shawna Deal, GVâ€™s very own elementary art teacher! Ms. Deal has taught at GV for 15 years. A graduate of Roberts Wesleyan College, Ms. Deal also serves as a yearbook advisor and oversees the elementary art club.

â€œI love the people I work with, the energy of the building, and the creativity that is fostered within GV. The excitement that is felt when students come to the art room or even when they anticipate coming to art is a favorite. I know what a joy art can be in my own life from when I was their age to where I am now in life. One art teacher in particular, Mary Cherniss, created a very safe and loving environment. It made me want to demonstrate that in my own teaching practices. Creating those unique bonds and connections with as many students as possible is so important.â€

In addition to her work at GV, Ms. Deal enjoys photography, spending time with family and friends, camping, cooking, creating art, making jewelry and other art pieces using repurposed ammo: https://www.facebook.com/BeautyandtheBrass.

post_text: Genesee Valley senior Gavin Hand signed a national letter of intent last week to swim at NCAA D-II Roberts Wesleyan College for the Roberts Wesleyan Redhawks in the fall where he will study sports management and marketing. Gavin was a 6-year varsity swimmer at GV, a 6-year Section V qualifier and 5-year Section V finalist. Gavin swam 42,350 yards (24 miles) during Varsity Meets, a GV school record. Gavin is pictured here with his parents Deanna and Tim Hand, as well as Sara Donlon (MS/HS Principal), Brian Edmister (Elementary Principal, Gavin's former Varsity Swim Coach and Club Coach), and Shawn Clancy (Varsity Swim Coach).

post_text: The results are in! The Elementary Student Council Sock Drive collected ONE THOUSAND two hundred and fifty seven socks! (That's alotta socks!) We're so proud of our kids who are developing a heart to serve. The socks will be donated to Wellspring Ministries, Healing Waters, the GV Nurse's Office and more. Special congrats to our third graders, the class who donated the most socks with 294 pairs. Well done!

post_text: Students in the JAG Design class presented t-shirts they designed and made for the Elementary Student Council. Pictured here along with the students are Ms. Emrich (student council advisor), Ms. Marciano (JAG Design co-teacher) and Mr. Gyr (Director of STEAM Learning, JAG Design co-teacher). JAG Design is a full-year elective course where students design and produce apparel, stickers and banners for school sports and clubs.
